## What happened

In **.NET 11**, **DSA was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` (and any DSA signing/verification) now throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS. It still works on Windows and Linux.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy DSA signatures**, you have two options:

### Option 1: Platform-guard DSA usage (keep legacy verification on Windows/Linux only)

```csharp
if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification not supported on macOS in .NET 11+");

using var dsa = DSA.Create();
dsa.ImportParameters(legacyPublicKey);
bool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

### Option 2: Migrate to a modern algorithm (recommended long-term)

Re-sign your data with **ECDSA** or **RSA**, then update the verification code:

```csharp
using var ecdsa = ECDsa.Create();
bool valid = ecdsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA256);
```

This requires re-generating signatures, so it's a larger change but eliminates the legacy algorithm dependency entirely.

### Option 3: Use a portable crypto library

If you must verify existing DSA signatures on all platforms including macOS, use a third-party library like **BouncyCastle** (`Portable.BouncyCastle`) which provides a managed DSA implementation independent of the OS.
